(PRT) has been detected. A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

Thought: The latest alert indicates ransomware behavior and suspicious activity on device `vnevado-win11u`. The detailed process logs show a process with command line `powershell -File C:\Scripts\get-userprttoken.ps1` and parent process `wmiprvse.exe -secured -Embedding`. This command line suggests a PowerShell script execution, which is often used in malicious activities such as token theft or lateral movement. This is likely the suspicious process involved in the user behavior change.

Action: submit[The command line of the suspicious process is: `powershell -File C:\Scripts\get-userprttoken.ps1`]

question_dict.context: A Mimikatz credential theft tool was detected on a device at 2024-07-04 22:35:03.797541+00:00. Mimikatz is a tool used to harvest plaintext passwords, password hashes, smartcard PINs, and Kerberos tickets. The attacker might be leveraging this tool to harvest credentials to log into this or other devices on the network by impersonating a valid user. To find relevant alerts, I should search for entries where `SourceComputerId` or `Entities` mention `vnevado-win11u` or related keywords indicating tampering or recovery setting changes.

Action: I will query the `SecurityAlert` table for entries where `SourceComputerId` or `Entities` mention `vnevado-win11u` and include keywords like "recovery", "tampering", or "configuration" in the `Description` or `Entities`.

[('e34d562e-ef12-4c4e-9bc0-7c6ae357c015', '2024-06-20 09:40:00.302895+00:00', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'High', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]', 'MDATP', 'Microsoft', '3e6bd315-8c89-4a24-8579-9601035ef416_1', '62857e21-c95b-4124-457c-3bdcef05583f', '', '', 'WindowsDefenderAtp', '', '', 'False', '2024-06-20 09:32:00.329557+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:32:03.749465+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:39:59.776942+00:00', '["1. tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'High', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]', 'MDATP', 'Microsoft', '3e6bd315-8c89-4a24-8579-9601035ef416_1', '62857e21-c95b-4124-457c-3bdcef05583f', '', '', 'WindowsDefenderAtp', '', '', 'False', '2024-06-20 09:32:00.329557+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:32:03.749465+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:44:53.379230+00:00', '["1. question_dict.context: A recent security incident involved the tampering of system recovery settings on the device `vnevado-win10r`. The process `vssblatemp.exe` was executed with the command `vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all`, indicating an attempt to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may include deleting all volume shadow copies to impede system restoration.
question_dict.question: Alongside the usage of `vssblatemp.exe`, another process was used to disable recovery features. What was the command and process ID of the other process involved?
question_dict.answer: Command: bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no, Process ID: 4312
solution: System recovery setting tampering has been detected on this device.

A security incident involving multiple alerts reported by various entities. You are a security analyst. 
You need to answer a given security question by querying the database.
The logs are stored in a MySQL database, you can use SQL queries to retrieve entries as needed.
Note there are more than 20 tables in the database, so you may need to explore the schema or check example entries to understand the database structure.

Your response should always be a thought-action pair:
Thought: <your reasoning>
Action: <your SQL query>

In Thought, you can analyse and reason about the current situation, 
Action can be one of the following: 
(1) execute[<your query>], which executes the SQL query
(2) submit[<your answer>], which is the final answer to the question

A security incident was reported involving Command and Control behavior being blocked, suggesting that malware was found running or had persistence mechanisms on the machine `vnevado-win10r`. The process id `1332` was observed running the command `curl http://vectorsandarrows.com` on this host with AadDeviceId `9d4887ba-0b69-47d6-89bc-9b32787f379e`. This malware was designated as active, requiring precautionary measures to be taken to check for residual infection signs. Can you identify the SID of the account associated with the suspicious remote activity observed on this machine?

Thought: The incident involves suspicious remote activity on the host `vnevado-win10r`, specifically a process executing `curl http://vectorsandarrows.com`. The relevant details include the process ID, command, and AadDeviceId. To find the SID of the account associated with this activity, I need to locate the process or activity logs linked to this host and process, then identify the user account involved.

First, I should identify the process details on `vnevado-win10r` with process ID `1332`. Then, I will look for user account information linked to this process or activity, which should include the SID.

Action: execute[SELECT * FROM processes WHERE hostname='vnevado-win10r' AND pid=1332]
ProgrammingError: Table 'env_monitor_db.processes' doesn't exist

Thought: The table `processes` does not exist in the database, indicating I need to explore the schema to find the relevant tables that store process or activity logs. Since there are many tables, I should first list all table names to identify where process or user activity data might be stored.

Action: execute[SHOW TABLES]

[('AADManagedIdentitySignInLogs',), ('AADNonInteractiveUserSignInLogs',), ('AADProvisioningLogs',), ('AADRiskyUsers',), ('AADServicePrincipalSignInLogs',), ('AADUserRiskEvents',), ('AlertEvidence',), ('AlertInfo',), ('AuditLogs',), ('AzureMetrics',), ('CloudAppEvents',), ('DeviceEvents',), ('DeviceFileCertificateInfo',), ('DeviceFileEvents',), ('DeviceImageLoadEvents',), ('DeviceInfo',), ('DeviceLogonEvents',), ('DeviceNetworkEvents',), ('DeviceNetworkInfo',), ('DeviceProcessEvents',), ('DeviceRegistryEvents',), ('EmailAttachmentInfo',), ('EmailEvents',), ('EmailUrlInfo',), ('Heartbeat',), ('IdentityDirectoryEvents',), ('IdentityLogonEvents',), ('IdentityQueryEvents',), ('MicrosoftAzureBastionAuditLogs',), ('MicrosoftGraphActivityLogs',), ('SecurityAlert',), ('SecurityIncident',), ('SigninLogs',), ('ThreatIntelligenceIndicator',), ('UrlClickEvents',), ('Usage',)]

Thought: The table `DeviceProcessEvents` appears to be the most relevant for investigating process-related activities on devices, including the suspicious process with PID 1332. To find details about this process on `vnevado-win10r`, I should query `DeviceProcessEvents` for entries matching the hostname and process ID. This table may contain user account information or session details linked to the process.

Action: execute[SELECT * FROM DeviceProcessEvents WHERE DeviceName='vnevado-win10r' AND ProcessId=1332]

Thought: The query returned no results, which suggests that either the process details are not logged in `DeviceProcessEvents` or the data has been purged. I should check for other related logs that might contain user or account information associated with the device or process, such as `DeviceLogonEvents` or `DeviceNetworkEvents`. Since the process involved remote activity, `DeviceNetworkEvents` might have relevant connection details, including user context or session info.

Action: execute[SELECT * FROM DeviceNetworkEvents WHERE DeviceName='vnevado-win10r' AND RemotePort IS NOT NULL]

Thought: No relevant entries were found in `DeviceNetworkEvents` either, indicating that the specific network activity or process details are not logged or have been purged. Given the available tables, the next logical step is to examine `DeviceLogonEvents`, which should record user logins and sessions on the device, potentially linking user accounts to device activity.

I will query `DeviceLogonEvents` for any logon sessions on `vnevado-win10r` around the time of the incident, to identify the user account involved.

Action: execute[SELECT * FROM DeviceLogonEvents WHERE DeviceName='vnevado-win10r']

Thought: The absence of entries in `DeviceLogonEvents` suggests that either logon events are not recorded in this table or the relevant data has been removed. Since direct logs are not available, I should consider other tables that might contain user or account identifiers linked to device activity, such as `DeviceInfo` or `AzureMetrics`. Alternatively, the incident details mention an AadDeviceId, which could be associated with user sign-in logs.

Given that, I will check `AADUserSignInLogs` for entries matching the `AadDeviceId` `9d4887ba-0b69-47d6-89bc-9b32787f379e` to find the user account involved.

Action: execute[SELECT * FROM AADUserSignInLogs WHERE DeviceId='9d4887ba-0b69-47d6-89bc-9b32787f379e']
ProgrammingError: Table 'env_monitor_db.AADUserSignInLogs' doesn't exist

Thought: The table `AADUserSignInLogs` does not exist, indicating that sign-in logs are stored elsewhere or under a different name. From the list of tables, `SigninLogs` appears to be the relevant table for sign-in activities associated with Azure AD or device sign-ins.

I will query `SigninLogs` for entries matching the `AadDeviceId` to identify the user account involved in the suspicious activity.

Action: execute[SELECT * FROM SigninLogs WHERE DeviceId='9d4887ba-0b69-47d6-89bc-9b32787f379e']]

What is the host name of the machine where suspicious 'GenRansom' behavior was detected, indicating the machine is actively running malware?

group', 'Manatee Tempest activity group', 'High', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

Validate the alert.
1. Check if the device owner or IT personnel had a legitimate reason to launch the command.
2. Look for recent signs of activity by the compromised user account and investigate them. Make sure to check other devices in your organization, as well as the original device associated with the compromised account.
3. Review device timelines for suspicious activity that may have occurred around the time of the alert.
4. Look for unfamiliar processes. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.
5. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors.
6. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other devices. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised devices.

B. Scope the incident. Find related devices, network addresses, and files in the incident graph.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach.
1. Stop suspicious processes, isolate affected systems, decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords, block IP addresses and URLs, and install security updates.
2. If you believe that you have a false positive, and a user has been suspended automatically, re-enable them via the MDI portal or Active Directory.

group', 'Manatee Tempest activity group', 'High', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

2. Look for recent signs of activity by the compromised user account or device and investigate them. Make sure to check other devices in your organization, as well as the original device associated with the compromised assets.
3. Review device timelines for suspicious activity that may have occurred around the time of the alert.
4. Look for unfamiliar processes. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.
5. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors.

B. Scope the incident. Find related devices, network addresses, and files in the incident graph.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach.
1. Stop suspicious processes, isolate affected systems, decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords, block IP addresses and URLs, and install security updates.
2. If you believe that the alert is a false positive:
     2.1 A user may have been suspended automatically. Revert the action by enabling the user account through the MDI portal or Active Directory.

A recent incident associated with this group involved a suspicious HTTP request to `vectorsandarrows.com` from the IP address `198.43.121.209` using the command line: `curl http://vectorsandarrows.com`, with process ID 6460. Additionally, system recovery setting tampering with the command `bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no` was observed, likely to hinder recovery options in case of system corruption. What is the process ID and the exact time when the `bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no` command was executed as part of the system recovery setting tampering?

Thought: To find the process ID and timestamp for the execution of the `bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no` command, I need to look into the system command execution logs. These logs are likely stored in a table that records command-line activities, including process IDs and timestamps. I will query the relevant table to locate entries where the command matches `bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no`.

Action: execute[SELECT process_id, execution_time FROM command_logs WHERE command_line = 'bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no']

Subsequent analysis revealed command and control behavior of malware which was blocked.
question_dict.question: What was the URL associated with the command and control behavior detected in the end alert?
solution: A known credential theft tool execution was detected on the host with AadDeviceId `4d8d23e9-a77d-4e33-9435-b8c457e57ca1`.
There was lateral movement to the jump server from the IP address `99.83.111.100` using PSExec.
Suspicious remote activity was observed on the account `dp5hn`.
Command and Control behavior was blocked for the URL `http://vectorsandarrows.com/`.

A security incident involving multiple malicious activities was detected. It started with a known credential theft tool, `mimikatz.exe`, being executed at two different times, indicating an attempt to dump users' credentials. This activity led to lateral movement attempts to the jump server and suspicious remote activities on the machine. Subsequent analysis revealed command and control behavior of malware which was blocked. What was the URL associated with the command and control behavior detected in the end alert?

Thought: The scenario describes multiple stages of malicious activity, culminating in a command and control (C2) behavior. The C2 activity is likely logged in a table that records network communications or alerts related to suspicious activities. To find the URL associated with the C2 behavior, I should look for entries indicating C2 or command-and-control alerts, possibly in a table related to network logs or alerts. Since the exact table names are unknown, I will start by examining the schema or sample entries from relevant tables that might contain network or alert data.

Action: SHOW TABLES;

[('AADManagedIdentitySignInLogs',), ('AADNonInteractiveUserSignInLogs',), ('AADProvisioningLogs',), ('AADRiskyUsers',), ('AADServicePrincipalSignInLogs',), ('AADUserRiskEvents',), ('AlertEvidence',), ('AlertInfo',), ('AuditLogs',), ('AzureMetrics',), ('CloudAppEvents',), ('DeviceEvents',), ('DeviceFileCertificateInfo',), ('DeviceFileEvents',), ('DeviceImageLoadEvents',), ('DeviceInfo',), ('DeviceLogonEvents',), ('DeviceNetworkEvents',), ('DeviceNetworkInfo',), ('DeviceProcessEvents',), ('DeviceRegistryEvents',), ('EmailAttachmentInfo',), ('EmailEvents',), ('EmailUrlInfo',), ('Heartbeat',), ('IdentityDirectoryEvents',), ('IdentityLogonEvents',), ('IdentityQueryEvents',), ('MicrosoftAzureBastionAuditLogs',), ('MicrosoftGraphActivityLogs',), ('SecurityAlert',), ('SecurityIncident',), ('SigninLogs',), ('ThreatIntelligenceIndicator',), ('UrlClickEvents',), ('Usage',)]

Thought: The most relevant tables for network activity and security alerts are likely `SecurityAlert`, `AlertEvidence`, and possibly `DeviceNetworkEvents`. Since the question pertains to a command and control (C2) URL detected in an alert, the `SecurityAlert` table seems the most promising, especially if it contains references to evidence or details about the alert. The `AlertEvidence` table might contain specific URLs or indicators associated with the alert. I will first check the `SecurityAlert` table for recent or relevant entries, then look into `AlertEvidence` for details like URLs.

Action: SELECT * FROM SecurityAlert LIMIT 5;

A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

A potential security incident involving a possible attempt to access a Primary Refresh Token (PRT) was detected. The process ID for this event was `7036`. This activity may have been an attempt by attackers to access the PRT to move laterally within the organization or perform credential theft. The Primary Refresh Token is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on various platforms and is essential for single sign-on (SSO) across applications. Can you identify the AadDeviceId related to this alert?

You are a security analyst. 
You need to answer a given security question by querying the database.
The logs are stored in a MySQL database, you can use SQL queries to retrieve entries as needed.
Note there are more than 20 tables in the database, so you may need to explore the schema or check example entries to understand the database structure.

Your response should always be a thought-action pair:
Thought: <your reasoning>
Action: <your SQL query>

In Thought, you can analyse and reason about the current situation, 
Action can be one of the following: 
(1) execute[<your query>], which executes the SQL query
(2) submit[<your answer>], which is the final answer to the question

A security incident involving system recovery setting tampering has been observed where a file `vssblatemp.exe` was launched on host `vnevado-win10s`, indicating potential adversary tampering to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services. Another file `bcdedit.exe` was also executed as part of this activity. Following this alert regarding system tampering, there was also a command and control behavior blocked. Can you identify the URL associated with the blocked behavior?

[('Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)', "Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) has been detected. A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

('Command and Control behavior was blocked', 'Malware and unwanted software are undesirable applications that perform annoying, disruptive, or harmful actions on affected machines. Some of these undesirable applications can replicate and spread from one machine to another. Others are able to receive commands from remote attackers and perform activities associated with cyber attacks.

A malware is considered active if it is found running on the machine or it already has persistence mechanisms in place. Active malware detections are assigned higher severity ratings.

A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

Tempest activity group', 'Manatee Tempest activity group', 'High', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'High', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]

Primary Refresh Token (PRT)', 'Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)', 'Medium', "Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) has been detected. A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

4. Look for unfamiliar processes. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.

B. Scope the incident. Find related devices, network addresses, and files in the incident graph.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach.

A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

A security incident involving suspicious 'GenRansom' behavior was detected on the host `vnevado-win11t` with AadDeviceId `e5799261-6720-4297-961e-bd9ca4275033`. Malware activity was found, necessitating precautionary measures. Additionally, there was an alert about system recovery setting tampering, where adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. During this incident, what specific command line was observed that could indicate system recovery setting tampering on the device?

Thought: To identify the specific command line associated with system recovery setting tampering, I need to locate logs related to command executions on the host `vnevado-win11t`. These logs should include command line details, and I should filter for entries that mention recovery settings or related suspicious commands. Since the incident involves tampering with recovery settings, commands like `bcdedit`, `reagentc`, or other system configuration commands are likely involved. I'll query the command execution logs for this host to find relevant entries.

Action: execute[SELECT * FROM command_logs WHERE hostname = 'vnevado-win11t' AND command_line LIKE '%recovery%' OR command_line LIKE '%bcdedit%' OR command_line LIKE '%reagentc%']

question_dict.question: On the same host `vnevado-win10s`, there was a tampering activity observed. Can you identify the command that was executed to disable the automatic Windows recovery features?

System recovery settings were tampered with using the `bcdedit` command line `bcdedit /set recoveryenabled no` at `2024-06-20T09:31:59.6743318Z`, with Process ID `4828`.

question_dict.context: A security incident involving the Manatee Tempest activity group was detected. This group is known for using drive-by downloads and other methods to gain initial access, followed by using malware tools for lateral movement. The incident started with a suspicious activity involving a URL `http://vectorsandarrows.com`, accessed from host `vnevado-win10r` with IP address `198.43.121.209` via a curl command. The ProcessId__CreatedTimeUtc__CommandLine is `1332__2024-06-20t09:10:52.7298237z__curl http://vectorsandarrows.com`.
question_dict.question: What is the host name of the device where 'CommandAndControl' malware was detected during lateral movement?
solution: Manatee Tempest, a Russia-based cybercriminal group, was involved in the use of access broker Mustard Tempest to facilitate infections and lateral movement using BLISTER loader and Cobalt Strike beacons on various networks. The group used domain fronting for command-and-control of Cobalt Strike.
A suspicious account with SID `S-1-5-21-1840191660-8534830288-125585561-1522` was identified in the context of the Manatee Tempest group activities.
The 'CommandAndControl' malware was detected on the host `vnevado-win10s`, indicating an attempt at lateral movement within the network.

question_dict.context: An incident occurred involving the potential compromise of devices showing ransomware-like behavior. An IP address associated with this is `99.83.111.100`, and files such as `get-userprttoken.ps1`, `characterical.zip`, and `characterical.zip.lockbit` were detected. Additionally, there was an incident of system recovery setting tampering. The tampering might involve adversaries deleting or removing system data and turning off recovery features to prevent system restoration.
question_dict.question: Can you identify the process command used that might have tampered with the system recovery settings?
solution: The device with AadDeviceId `e5799261-6720-4297-961e-bd9ca4275033` is potentially compromised and exhibiting ransomware-like behavior.

Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

'Manatee Tempest activity group', 'High', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

'Manatee Tempest activity group', 'High', 'The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware lexpaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

question_dict.question: What command line and process ID were used for the tampering of system recovery settings observed earlier?

System recovery setting tampering was observed using the process `vssblatemp.exe` deleting all volume shadow copies with Process ID `1900` at `2024-06-20t09:32:02.4640548z`.

tampering', 'System recovery setting tampering', 'High', 'System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssblatemp.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssblatemp.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbblatemp.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbblatemp.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]', 'MDATP', 'Microsoft', '3e6bd315-8c89-4a24-8579-9601035ef416_1', '62857e21-c95b-4124-457c-3bdcef05583f', '', '', 'WindowsDefenderAtp', '', '', 'False', '2024-06-20 09:32:00.329557+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:32:03.749465+00:00', '2024-06-20 09:39:59.776942+00:00', '["1. Validate the alert.
1. Check if the device owner or IT personnel had a legitimate reason to launch the command.
2. Look for recent signs of activity by the compromised user account or device and investigate them. Make sure to check other devices in your organization, as well as the original device associated with the compromised assets.
3. Review device timelines for suspicious activity that may have occurred around the time of the alert.
4. Look for unfamiliar processes. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.
5. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors.
6. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other devices. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised devices.

B. Scope the incident. Find related devices, network addresses, and files in the incident graph.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach.
1. Stop suspicious processes, isolate affected systems, decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords, block IP addresses and URLs, and install security updates.
2. If you believe that the alert is a false positive:
     2.1 A user may have been suspended automatically. Revert the action by enabling the user account through the MDI portal or Active Directory.
     2.2 Devices may have been automatically contained. Revert the action through the device page in the portal.

access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)', 'Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)', 'Medium', "Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) has been detected. A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

On 2024-07-10, at 11:24:45.260113+00:00, a security incident was detected involving lateral movement to the jump server `vnevado-jump` from host `vnevado-win10v` with associated account `tgs2z` (email: `tgs2z@vnevado.alpineskihouse.co`). The source IP address involved in this activity was `141.216.110.153`. During this incident, there have been numerous file system changes indicating possible ransomware activity. Can you determine the destination IP address where potential lateral movement was observed following the suspicious network event?

Thought: The incident details mention lateral movement from `vnevado-win10v` to `vnevado-jump` involving a specific account and source IP. To find the destination IP address involved in this lateral movement, I should look for network activity logs around the specified timestamp, focusing on connections originating from `vnevado-win10v` or involving the account `tgs2z`. I will query the network activity logs to identify any connections from the source IP `141.216.110.153` or from the host `vnevado-win10v` that target the jump server `vnevado-jump`. The goal is to find the IP address of the destination host involved in this lateral movement.

Action: 
```sql
SELECT DISTINCT destination_ip
FROM network_logs
WHERE 
    (source_ip = '141.216.110.153' OR source_host = 'vnevado-win10v')
    AND timestamp BETWEEN '2024-07-10 11:24:45' AND '2024-07-10 11:30:00'
    AND destination_host = 'vnevado-jump';
```
